<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"Solve_Linear_Program_Using_OpenSolver"=
>Solve Linear Program Using OpenSolver</h2>



<p>In reality, a linear program can contain 30 to 1000 variables and solvin=
g it either Graphically or Algebraically is next to impossible. Companies g=
enerally use OpenSolver to tackle these real-world problems. Here I am gonn=
a take you through steps to solve a linear program using OpenSolver.</p>



<p>OpenSolver is an open-source linear and <a href=3D"https://www.analytics=
vidhya.com/blog/2021/10/a-comprehensive-guide-on-deep-learning-optimizers//=
?utm_source=3Dkeyword" rel=3D"nofollow"><strong>optimizer</strong></a> for =
Microsoft Excel. It is an advanced version of a built-in Excel Solver. You =
can download OpenSolver <a href=3D"https://sourceforge.net/projects/opensol=
ver/files/latest/download" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"><s=
trong>here</strong></a> and follow the installation&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://=
opensolver.org/installing-opensolver/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener no=
referrer"><strong>manual</strong></a>.</p>



<p>I want you to get hands-on knowledge of using OpenSolver. So, for a clea=
r understanding, I will explain it using an example.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-example-1"><strong>Example</strong><=
/h3>



<p>Below there is a diet chart that gives me calories, protein, carbohydrat=
e and fat content for 4 food items. Sara wants a diet with minimum cost. Th=
e diet chart is as follows:</p>



<div>
<div>
<div class=3D"table-responsive">
<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Food Item 1</td>
<td>&nbsp;Food Item 2</td>
<td>&nbsp;Food Item 3</td>
<td>&nbsp;Food Item 4</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Calories</td>
<td>400</td>
<td>&nbsp;200</td>
<td>&nbsp;150</td>
<td>&nbsp;500</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Protien (in grams)</td>
<td>3</td>
<td>&nbsp;2</td>
<td>&nbsp;0</td>
<td>&nbsp;0</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Carbohydrates ( in grams)</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>&nbsp;2</td>
<td>&nbsp;4</td>
<td>&nbsp;4</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Fat (in grams)</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>&nbsp;4</td>
<td>&nbsp;1</td>
<td>&nbsp;5</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Cost</td>
<td>$0.50</td>
<td>&nbsp;$0.20</td>
<td>&nbsp;$0.30</td>
<td>$0.80</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>



<p>The chart gives the nutrient content as well as the per-unit cost of eac=
h food item. The diet has to be planned in such a way that it should contai=
n at least 500 calories, 6 grams of protein, 10 grams of carbohydrates and =
8 grams of fat.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-solution-1">Solution</h3>



<p>First, I=E2=80=99m gonna formulate my linear program in a spreadsheet.</=
p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-1-nbsp-identify-the-decision-va=
riables">Step 1:&nbsp;Identify the decision variables</h4>



<p>Here my decision variables are the food items. Add the headers. For tria=
l purposes, we are entering arbitrary values. Let=E2=80=99s say, Sara consu=
mes 3 units of Food Item 1, 0 unit of Food Item 2, 1 &nbsp;unit of Food Ite=
m 3 and 0 unit of Food Item 4. These are called variable cells.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"60=
0" height=3D"124" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/wp-content/uploads=
/2024/08/DP_124375.webp" alt=3D"Identifying decision variables in OpenSolve=
r [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-190269" loading=3D"lazy">=
</figure></div>


<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-2-now-we-will-write-our-objecti=
ve-function">Step 2: Now we will write our objective function</h4>



<p>For the diet to be optimal we must have minimum cost along with required=
 calories, protein, carbohydrate, and fat.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"600" height=3D"146" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/08/DP_2177062.webp" alt=3D"Objective function in Ope=
nSolver [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-190270"></figure></=
div>


<p>In cell B7:E7&nbsp; we take the reference to the number of units. And in=
 cell B8:E8 we put the per-unit cost of each food item.</p>



<p>In cell B10, we want the total cost of the diet. The total cost is given=
 by the sumproduct of the number of units eaten and per-unit cost. Sumprodu=
ct is given by =3D B7*B8+C7*C8+D7*D8+E7*E8. Let=E2=80=99s see this in a spr=
eadsheet.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"600" height=3D"313" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/08/DP_3135537.webp" alt=3D"Solving LP with OpenSolve=
r (Step 2) [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-190271"></figure=
></div>


<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-3-nbsp-now-we-will-enter-the-co=
nstraints">Step 3:&nbsp;Now, we will enter the constraints</h4>



<p>Column F contains a total of calories, protein, carbohydrate, and fat. T=
he total number of calorie intake in given by sumproduct the number of food=
 items eaten and the calorie consumed per food item. For cell F13=3D Sumpro=
dcut($B$7:$F$7, B13:F13). Similarly for others. Column G gives the inequali=
ty since the problem demands Calories, Protein, Carbohydrate and Fat to be =
at least 500, 6, 10 and 8 respectively. Column H gives the required nutrien=
t content.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"600" height=3D"260" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsv=
idhya.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/DP_4172588.webp" alt=3D"Constraints in=
 OpenSolver [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-190273" style=
=3D"width:852px;height:auto"></figure></div>


<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-4-nbsp-now-we-will-enter-the-li=
near-program-into-the-solver">Step 4:&nbsp;Now, we will enter the Linear pr=
ogram into the solver</h4>



<p>Once you have installed OpenSolver. When you click on the Data tab, on t=
he right you will see Model. Click on the model, then enter the values one =
by one. First, we will enter the objective function,$B10 i.e in the objecti=
ve cell. Select minimize because we want to minimize the diet cost.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
