=3D"async" width=3D"560" height=3D"149" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.=
com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/image-5154736.webp" alt=3D"LP solution by No=
rthwest Corner Method [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-19028=
4"></figure>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Least Cost Method</h4>



<p>Least Cost method is another method to calculate the most feasible solut=
ion for a linear programming problem. This method derives more accurate res=
ults than the Northwest Corner method. It is used for transportation and ma=
nufacturing problems. </p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-example-4">Example</h4>



<p>To keep it simple I am explaining the above transportation problem.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"503" height=3D"137" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.=
com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/image-5388232.webp" alt=3D"Transportation LP=
 problem [Linear programming problem]" class=3D"wp-image-190285"></figure>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-solution-4">Solution</h4>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-1-understanding-the-least-cost-=
method">Step 1: Understanding the Least Cost Method</h4>



<p>According to the least cost method, you start from the cell containing t=
he least unit cost for transportation. So, for the above problem, I supply =
5 units from Silo 3 at a per-unit cost of $4. The demand for Mill1 is met. =
For Mill 2, we supply 15 units from Silo 1 at a per-unit cost of $2. Then F=
or Mill 3 we supply 15 units from Silo 2 at a per-unit cost of $9. Then for=
 Mill 4 we supply 10 units from Silo 2 at a per unit cost of $20 and 5 unit=
s from Silo 3 an $18 per unit. The total transportation costs are $475.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-step-2-optimizing-costs-with-excel-s=
olver">Step 2: Optimizing Costs with Excel Solver</h4>



